The actions and activities of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members who hold public officean elected office in a council or parliament, and of all endorsed candidates for the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, must be consistent with the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution of the Greens, and with the Objectives of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria laid down in this Constitution. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members who hold public officean elected office in a council or parliament as endorsed candidates of the Greens will also adhere to the policies of the Greens, except that, in rare or special circumstances where the views of an elected Member are in conflict with the Greens’ policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, then that elected Member may vote according to their conscience. When an elected Member or candidate recognises a potential conflict between their conscience and the Greens’ policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, then such an elected representative or candidate will furnish a statement accounting for this position to the State Council, and in the case of a member of Federal Parliament, to the National Council of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, for their information. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members elected to, or candidates for, positions in local government will provide such a statement to their Branch, where the circumstances require it. The obligation of an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria public officer to comply with Greens policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do is met when that Member complies with the approved Greens policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do relevant to their jurisdiction. Where more than one AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member is elected to any jurisdiction, each elected Member has an obligation to attempt to reach a consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so position on all substantive matters before them. When an elected AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member does not vote for the implementation of an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, then they will, at the earliest opportunity, furnish a statement to the State Council, accounting for the reason why he or she so voted. Members in public officean elected office in a council or parliament may hold meetings with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members in their electorate from time to time and will do so within thirty days of being requested to do so by: ten percent or50. (whichever is the lesser) of the Members in the relevant electorate; or a Branch or Branches representing one-third of the Members in the electorate; or State Council in the case of the Senator(s) representing Victoria. The agenda for an electorate meeting will include any matters placed on it by the public officean elected office in a council or parliament holder or by the Members requesting the meeting, or by any Branch within the electorate. Electorate meetings do not have binding decision-making power. Subject to clause 51.10, members who hold public officean elected office in a council or parliament must not:
documents.s: Greens in Public Officean elected office in a council or parliament

documents.t: Election Period: Defined as the period from when nominations for any election are opened until the election occurs. Probity Check: A probity check investigates the background of an individual to determine their suitability to be a candidate. Decision-making period: The period when the Probity Panel considers and comes to a decision about a nominee being the time commencing when all probity-related nomination documentation has been sent to the Probity Panel, and concluding when a probity decision has been reported to the Returning Officer.

There shall be established a Probity Panel whose duty it is to carry out all probity checks on all nominees for external positions. The purpose of the Probity Panel is to judge the suitability of members who nominate to stand as candidates in external elections. In so doing, it is not the task of the Probity Panel to make conclusive findings of fact in relation to any matter adverse to a nominee, nor is this necessary for the Probity Panel to reject a nomination. Noting that the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution states [at 8.1] that “All AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members are entitled to the following benefits: … (f) To be eligible to seek nomination for public officean elected office in a council or parliament as a candidate for the Greens (NCNational Council 9.8), subject to clause 56.13”, probity should only be rejected where there are compelling and serious reasons why, in the interests of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, the member should be deemed not suitable to stand as a candidate. The paramount duty of the Probity Panel is to make decisions in the best interests of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. The Probity Panel will, in this regard, consider the values, policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do positions and political imperatives of the party in making all decisions.

There will be a minimum of 11 people appointed to the Probity Panel. Probity Panel members will be appointed by State Council, as per Schedule 1, for a term of 2 years. Their terms will run from the date of appointment to two years from the date of their appointment. Members of the Probity Panel and any Sub-Panels should to the greatest extent possible be disinterested persons in relation any matter they consider. The Probity Panel will appoint its convenor and secretary. All Probity Panel members must be members of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1). A Probity Sub-Panel shall be comprised of between three and seven members. Members of a particular Sub-Panel will be appointed by the Probity Panel as a whole, or by a person or persons assigned by the Probity Panel to do this, in which case the composition of each Sub-Panel so appointed will be reported to the next meeting of the Probity Panel. Members of a Probity Sub-Panel must not include any individual: appointed as Returning Officer or as an advisor to a Returning Officer for a position which the sub-panel is considering. who is a nominee or nominator for a position which the sub-panel is considering. who is a fellow branch member of a nominee for a position which the sub-panel is considering. who would be perceived to have a conflict of interest in relation to a nominee or the position which the sub-panel is considering. Members of the Probity Panel may not carry out probity checks or be involved in those checks in any way where a nomination is related to any campaign in which they are involved. Casual vacancies on the Probity Panel may be filled by the State Council or State Executive following a call for expressions of interest via the appropriate internal Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) communication methods, as per Schedule 1.

Any decision of the Probity Panel must be made by at least 3 of its members (a sub-panel). Consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so decisions of a sub-panel shall be decisions of the Probity Panel. Subject to this bylaw, deliberations of the Probity Panel are confidential. All Probity Panel members will sign a confidentiality agreement. A record of all nominations, the related investigations and findings will be securely maintained by the State Secretary. Records of nominations are confidential to the Probity Panel and the Returning Officer in the first instance. However the State Executive, Victorian Campaign Committee and any relevant preselecting body (where a preselection panel has been appointed) will have the right to inspect the record of any individual where they are considering a matter related to and relevant to that member. The Probity Panel may meet in person or via electronic means, including email. The Probity Panel will keep minutes of all its meetings and records of its activities. The Probity Panel will report in written form on its activities: To the State Conference annually, To the Victorian Campaign Committee monthly during Local, State or Federal election periods. At any time as requested by the Victorian Campaign Committee, State Executive or State Council.

Noting that the paramount duty of the Probity Panel is to make decisions in the best interests of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, the Probity Panel should, so far as consistent with this duty, keep in mind fairness to the nominee in the conduct of any probity check. A probity check will be conducted on all nominees for public officean elected office in a council or parliament, excepting any nominee who has been approved by a Probity Panel within the previous 3 years; and provides a statutory declaration stating that no matters relevant to probity have substantially changed since their last Probity check; and the most senior staff memberState Director member, Convenor of the Misconduct Panel, and Victorian Campaign Committee Convenor and electorate or regional campaign committee convenor can confirm that no matters relevant to probity have substantially changed since their last probity check. By the close of nominations, nominees must submit: a completed Probity Form as prescribed from time to time by the VCCVictorian Campaign Committee; a signed Statutory Declaration attesting to the correctness of the Preselection and Probity Forms, and agreeing to a Police Check if the Returning Officer or Probity Panel deem it necessary; any other document or form requested by the Probity Panel or a Probity sub-panel. provided that a nominee who has been approved by a Probity Panel within the previous 3 years may provide the statutory declaration described in clause 24(b) above in substitution for the documents required in this clause and a check will be conducted with the most senior staff member and Victorian Campaign Committee or relevant election campaign committee Convenor to confirm this. The Returning Officer shall pass any envelopes or attachments containing the probity documents to the Probity Panel unopened. The Probity Panel is empowered to carry out any investigations it deems necessary into any nomination. Each probity check shall include, at a minimum: scrutiny of the probity form and accompanying Statutory Declaration; assiduous and reasonable searches of available online information about the nominee, their professional and community organisation affiliations, and their media presence, if any (except if the nominee is an elected representative); a request for any relevant information from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Misconduct Panel; an invitation for input from local Branch and regional bodies’ office bearers and party officials; consideration of any objections to or concerns about probity raised by other Members. and assessment of nominees after appropriate input from local Branch and regional bodies’ office bearers, party officials and other members as considered necessary. The nominee shall provide: All names that they have used or previously been known by, All pseudonyms that they use or have previously used, Access to all Probity sub-panel members of all social media and online engagement accounts currently in use by the nominee or which were in use within the previous five (5) years. This access shall be maintained for the duration of the decision-making period. This access may include, for example, allowing Probity sub-panel members to ‘friend’ them on Facebook, ensuring Probity sub-panel members can ‘follow’ all of the nominee’s Twitter accounts and ensuring any other action is taken which provides the Probity sub-panel members such access. The Probity Panel may contact any person while conducting a probity check without reference to the nominee. Confidentiality will be maintained as follows: Any person contacted by the Probity Panel will be advised of the confidential nature of the process in that they should not disclose that the person has nominated, nor should they disclose the questions asked by or their response made to the Probity Panel to any other person. All responses received by the Probity Panel shall be kept confidential to the Probity Panel and shall only be disclosed as a non-identifying summary should clause 41 be enacted.

The Probity Panel shall make a finding for each nomination received by the end of the decision-making period that the nomination be: approved, or approved subject to certain conditions outlined by the Probity Panel, or approved noting risk/communication matters if preselected, or rejected. A sub-panel may only make this finding by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so. Should consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so not be achieved the nomination will be considered by the full Probity Panel, at which a majority will be required to make the finding. Subject to 34, 39 and 40 below, the decision-making period must be no later than fourteen (14) days (or 48 hours in the case of a snap election) after the close of nominations. In the case of a nominee being approved with conditions, the State Director, or their delegate, will be informed in writing within 72 hours by the Probity Panel. If the nominee gains preselection, the convenor of the relevant body responsible for the preselection will be provided a summary of conditions by the Probity Panel. The convenor of the relevant body responsible for preselection will be tasked with tracking compliance of conditions. Any breaches of conditions must then be referred to the Endorsement Review Committee. The Probity Panel shall have the authority to: request further statutory declarations from any nominee should the panel judge that more information be required to make an assessment on any nomination. interview any nominee should the panel judge that more information be required to make an assessment on any nomination. In these circumstances, the decision-making period may be extended to allow reasonable time for the nominee to comply. If the nomination is approved subject to certain conditions or rejected, the decision shall be considered to be an interim decision until the process at 39 – 40 is complete, whereby a final decision will be made. The Probity Panel members considering a nomination shall reject any nomination where: the sub-panel judges that the candidacy of the nominee concerned would be inappropriate, the sub-panel judges that the candidacy of the nominee would be detrimental to the Australian Greens Victoria on grounds relating to past conduct, character or reputation, the candidate has not given an undertaking to support stated party policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, subject to clause 51.2 of the constitution, or in lieu of that undertaking, has not provided pre-selectors with an explanation as to which policies the candidate does not support. The Probity Panel shall have the authority to reject any nomination on the grounds that the nominee: refuses to co-operate with the probity panel fails to comply with any conditions outlined in the relevant Code of Conduct forms fails to comply with any conditions outlined in the Confidentiality Agreement fails to comply with any condition imposed upon the nominee in relation to their nomination (as per 35 (b) above) holds a public position in opposition to Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, and the probity sub-panel deems the matter to be so serious as to damage the party’s electoral opportunities. Prima facie a serious falsehood or apparent serious concealment of facts or issues in probity forms is grounds for a nomination to be rejected. Where the Probity Panel rejects a nomination, the nominee may not nominate for any other position at the same election. When an interim decision is made to either approve a nomination subject to certain conditions or reject a nomination, the following will occur: The Probity sub-panel will prepare a document setting out the reasons for the decision. The nominee will be provided with the reasons for decision and shall have 48 hours to provide a response to the Probity sub-panel. The reasons for the decision may include a summary of feedback received, without breaching the confidentiality requirements at clause 31. The Probity sub-panel will consider any response from the nominee in making a final decision. A final decision will be made within 48 hours of receipt of any response from the nominee. If the nominee fails to provide a response, the original decision will stand. In these circumstances, the decision-making period may be extended to allow for these processes to occur. Clause 38 above shall not apply in the circumstances of a snap-election. When a decision is approved noting that risk and/or communications matters require attention, the Returning Officer will notify the Probity Panel of the nominee’s preselection. Then the convenor of the Probity Panel will then inform the State Director. In consultation, either the convenor of the Probity Panel or the State Director, or their delegate, will inform the convenor of the relevant body responsible for the preselection in writing of the risk and communications issues which require a plan. Decisions of the Probity Panel: will be reported to the relevant Returning Officer and the nominee within 24 hours of the decision may be appealed to the State Executive.

A nominee will be informed of who is on the Probity Panel and which members will be reviewing their nomination. A nominee will be informed as soon as practical of any decision by the Probity Panel in relation to their nomination, in accordance with clauses 32 and 38 above. A nominee may provide a written response to any decision to approve their nomination subject to conditions, or to reject their nomination, in accordance with clause 38 above. A nominee may appeal a decision of the Probity Panel to the State Executive in accordance with clause 41 above within 24 hours of receipt of any decision to approve their nomination subject to conditions, or to reject their nomination. A decision will be made by State Executive within 24 hours of the appeal. A nomination for any position is considered confidential until the nominations close and the Probity Panel has completed its work. Until that time nominations may be withdrawn without prejudice. After that time an announcement of the nominations will be made on the internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria website.

All records in relation to the making of a decision in respect of a probity decision shall be kept securely and separately for a period of 5 years, provided that Police Checks will be securely destroyed as soon as they are no longer needed. The State Secretary will have the responsibility of safe custody. All members of the Probity Panel will be responsible for permanently deleting any electronic copies they hold of documents related to Probity Panel decisions (other than Panel minutes) within one month of the election with respect to which the probity decisions related.

The process for the appointment of a member to the Probity Panel is that: The notice of vacancy, seeking expressions of interest from suitable members, is distributed to the membership. Expressions of interest and curriculum vitae forwarded to the Probity Panel Convenor, or should that position by vacant, the Convenor of the Victorian Campaign Committee Prospective member will be interviewed by a panel made up of the Probity Panel Convenor (or other member of the Probity Panel), the State Convenor and the Convenor of the Victorian Campaign Committee. The panel will: discuss the responsibility of the position, in particular trust implications ensure the applicant understand the duration of the appointment ensure the applicant is prepared to sign a confidentiality agreement on appointment ensure that the applicant has the personal and professional aptitude ensure the applicant has been actively participating in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria by being involved in branch, campaigning and/or State Council activities ensure the applicant has a demonstrated capacity or experience to exercise political judgment, e.g. has held leadership positions in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria or related organisations ensure the applicant has a reference from a Branch or State office bearer That panel will make a recommendation to State Council or State Executive

In this chapter:

A member or former member expelled under clause 91.2 (the applicant) may apply to, and only to, the Administrative Review Panel for a finding that a decision of a member or party body (other than the Administrative Review Panel): did not comply with this Constitution or the bylaws; or

The Administrative Review Panel is composed of 5 members appointed by State Council. The term of appointment of a member of the Administrative Review Panel is 2 years. To be eligible to be appointed to and remain a member of the Administrative Review Panel, a member: must have been a member for the past 2 years; must not be: a member who holds public officeincludes a member elected or appointed to a public office where the term of that office is yet to begin; (ii) a member who has held public officean elected office in a council or parliament in the last 5 years (except as a local councillor); (iii) a member of State Executive; (iv) a member of any party body that has the task of judging the suitability of members to be considered for preselection as, or to remain, candidates in external elections; (v) a member of the Misconduct Panel; (vi) an insolvent under administrationhas the meaning given in the Interpretation of Legislation Act 1984; (vii) a represented person; or (viii) an employee of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; and 3. must not have been the subject of a sanction that was imposed or which had effect within the past 3 years. The Administrative Review Panel has a Convenor who is appointed by the Administrative Review Panel from its members. A meeting of the Administrative Review Panel may be convened by:
State Council may make a bylaw that provides:

If a member is experiencing interpersonal difficulties with another member or members, they may request assistance from the Mediation Panel. The Mediation Panel may, after making reasonable enquiries of the members involved:

The Mediation Panel is composed of 3 members appointed by State Council. The term of appointment of a member of the Mediation Panel is 2 years. To be eligible to be appointed to and remain a member of the Mediation Panel, a member must not be: a member who has held public officean elected office in a council or parliament in the last12. months; a member of State Executive; or an employee of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. The quorum for meetings of the Mediation Panel is 2. The Mediation Panel must not be granted or have imposed upon it, and must not accept, further powers or obligations.
State Council may make a bylaw that provides:

The purpose of this Chapter is to regulate the formation, adoption and management of processes for electoral and continuous campaigning for the political purposes of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. State Council may make bylaws to facilitate any element of the processes outlined hereunder. Although Branches are recognised as the primary organising unit for election purposes, this Constitution authorises the creation of regional campaign committees based on such boundaries as State Council may determine, to facilitate election management and continuous campaigning where they are best managed across more than one Branch or group of Branches. To facilitate the management of electoral and continuous campaigning on a state-wide basis, this Constitution authorises the creation of a Standing Committee of State Council for electoral and continuous campaigning purposes. State electoral and continuous campaigning policies will be formulated with the maximum participation of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members and Branches through the meeting procedures outlined in chapter 3.6, and must actively consider input from relevant expert persons or bodies, including that provided by the national office of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) and any elected Greens public official.

Reporting to State Council, the formulation of state-wide AGVAustralian Greens Victoria electoral and continuous campaigning policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do and the management of its application will be the responsibility of the Victorian Campaign Committee created as a Standing Committee of State Council under this Chapter. The Victorian Campaign Committee is responsible for:

The Convenor of the Victorian Campaign Committee will be elected by all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members by annual postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ (though if the position remains unfilled after the annual postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ for any reason, that position may be elected by all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members present at the Annual Conference or at a Special State Conference by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or, failing this consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so, by a secret ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members present), and will be a voting member of the State

State Council may enact bylaws to determine the method to be used for pre-selecting candidates to stand for any election as an endorsed AGVAustralian Greens Victoria candidate. In lieu of any bylaws, State Council will, in good time before each general election for federal parliament, state parliament and local government, determine the method to be used for pre-selecting candidates to stand at that election as an endorsed AGVAustralian Greens Victoria candidate. In either case, State Council may determine different methods for individual electorates or positions on a ticket in a given election, such as differentiating between targeted electorates or lead candidates and other electorates or candidates, and the determined method or methods must be used consistently by all Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) bodies in Victoria responsible for conducting pre-selections for that election.

The decision on the allocation of preferences for local government electorates may be made by Branches, subject to Schedule 1 where there is more than one Branch in a Local Government Area. If there is any ambiguity as to whether a Branch has authority in a particular case, the dispute will be resolved by the State Council. Any Branch may delegate the responsibility for deciding preference allocation to State Council. The decision on the allocation of preferences for any electorate that is not a local government municipality will be made by State Council or the body to which State Council delegates that power, having consulted with the Branches to which the electorate corresponds.

❗This power must not be delegated. An ‘applicant’ for AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership is a natural person whose membership application and fee has been received by the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. An individual may apply for AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership by paying the applicable membership fee and by completing and submitting the membership application form which will contain, but is not limited to, the following information: the name of the applicant; the residential address, including postcode, of the applicant; the postal address of the applicant, as well as the phone, fax, email or other electronic contacts; A declaration signed by the applicant that they agree to be bound by the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution and constitutional rules of the Greens; A declaration signed by the applicant that the applicant is not a member of any other political partya political party registered under Commonwealth, state or territory law or its subordinate bodies and will not join such organisations whilst remaining an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member (see clause 7.5(c)). ❗This power must not be delegated. The following bodies will have the power to admit an applicant as a Member: A Branch covering the area where the Member resides; The State Council or State Executive in respect of any application from an applicant where there is no relevant Branch; and The State Council or State Executive in respect of any application from an applicant where the relevant Branch has been aware of but failed to consider an application for at least35. days. Provided that should the relevant Branch or the State Executive at any time resolve that any person’s application should be deferred for further consideration, or rejected, then no body (other than the body which resolved to defer or reject the application) may later admit that person to membership and no admission to membership made in error shall be valid. This shall not limit State Council’s right to admit a person to membership. Each application will be processed according to any bylaws formulated by the State Council. An applicant will be welcomed as a new AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member, provided that person: has read and agreed to the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution and agreed to abide by the constitutional rules of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; agrees to join the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and to be registered to a Branch (where one is established which covers the applicant) according to residential address; is not a member of a proscribed organisation, and agrees to refrain from joining a proscribed organisation whilst remaining an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member; pays an annual membership fee; complies, if applicable, with clause 56.16; acknowledges and agrees that certain personal information collected by the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria may be provided to State and Federal electoral authorities in accordance with legislative requirements; acknowledges and agrees that their personal information may be passed on to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626; and is approved for membership by a Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) body in accordance with 7.3. Notwithstanding 7.1, 7.2 and 7.3, a person who is a financial member of a political partya political party registered under Commonwealth, state or territory law which is a member party of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 other than the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria (the ‘other party’) may, if they have moved to the State of Victoria or will imminently do so, request membership of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. In such circumstances, the State Secretary or person appointed by the State Secretary may admit the person as a Member, provided that the information listed at 7.21. to (e), and any prescribed fee, has been provided either by the person or the other party, and provided that membership of the person to the other party ceases upon the person’s admission to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. Where any doubt arises as to whether the admission of a person under this clause is appropriate, the matter may be referred to the State Executive for decision.

All AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members are entitled to the following benefits: To be registered as members of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626; To participate in discussion, debate and decision-making in Greens meetings, according to the constitutional arrangements of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; To communicate with the entire State membership about matters pertaining to the Greens through the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria’s State publications, within reason and constrained by space, cost and time limitations: similar considerations apply to the publications of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626; To participate in local, State and national policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do formation according to the constitutional rules and bylaws of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; to be eligible to be elected to and to hold a position as an office bearer, delegate or other position in a Branch, the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, or the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, subject to any bylaws limiting this entitlement in specific circumstances (such as term limits preventing holding multiple positions, or holding positions in conjunction with public officean elected office in a council or parliament, or like circumstances); To be eligible to seek nomination for public officean elected office in a council or parliament as a candidate for the Greens, subject to clause 56.13; At any reasonable time, to inspect without charge the books, records and securities of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; Upon request, to receive a copy of the audited accounts of the previous year. Such a request is to be made in writing, and will be subject to a reasonable charge to cover printing and postage, but the requested copy must be provided within a reasonable time by the Greens; and To receive a copy of the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution, a copy of the State Constitution, and a copy of the National Constitutionthe Constitution of the Australian Greens upon request. Upon request, and within 14 days of the request, to receive minutes of general meetings of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and any associated financial statements. For any election or ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’, and subject to the terms of any bylaw prescribing otherwise, the persons deemed to be AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members will be only those persons who were AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members as at: the date of the close of nominations in the case of a person standing for election; the date of the close of voting in the case of a person casting the vote; or such other date as may be set by the body calling the vote or by the returning officer, provided that the date is not later than the close of voting.

The State Council will develop bylaws for the regulation of membership fees. Each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member will pay membership fees directly to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. Membership fees will fall due annually and will be paid in advance for a period of12. months, but may be paid in instalments if this is allowed by the bylaws. In this clause, ‘Membership Term’ means the12. month period for which the membership fees have been paid. Before expiry of an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member’s Membership Term, the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member will be sent, to their nominated contact address, which may be a postal address or an email address, a renewal notice specifying: the date that the Membership Term is due to expire (‘Expiry Date’); how to renew their membership, including the amount to be paid; and such other matters as may be specified in the bylaws. Membership will lapse and the person will no longer be an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member if the membership fee remains unpaid at the later of: the Expiry Date of the Membership Term; and 60 days after the renewal notice was sent. Notwithstanding clauses 9.5 and 9.6, if a renewal notice is not sent and the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member fails to pay the membership fee, their membership will automatically lapse nine months after the Expiry Date of her or his Membership Term. There will be no special joining or rejoining fees. Membership fees are not refundable, once the applicant has been formally accepted as an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member. No AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member will pay or cause to be paid, directly or indirectly, the membership fees of three or more persons including their own membership in any year. State Council will, upon the presentation of sufficient evidence, and after giving all affected AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members the opportunity to be heard, declare void the membership of any person whose membership fees have been paid only because of a violation of clause 9.10.

An AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member may not be registered in more than one Branch, although the Member may work in several. An AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member is eligible for Branch office and decision-making only in the Branch in which the Member is registered. For purposes of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership, the National Council and State Council can rule on whether an organisation is to be considered a proscribed organisation. The decisions of State Council will be ratified by the National Council. The membership status, contact details and other personal information of any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member will not be released to any non-Member or organisation without the authorisation of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member, other than State and Federal electoral authorities, and the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626.

An AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member may resign from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria by notifying the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria in writing. The notice will be presented at the next meeting of the relevant Branch, and at State Council if appropriate.

The body known as THE AUSTRALIAN GREENS – Victoria is: the Victorian member body of the confederation of state-based political parties known as the ‘Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626’; registered with the Australian Electoral Commission (the AECAustralian Electoral Commission) under the name of ‘Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626’ and registered with the Victorian Electoral Commission (the VECVictorian Election Commission) under the name of ‘The Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 – Victoria’; registered with the Registrar of Incorporated Associations under the name of ‘The Greens Victoria Inc.’; and abbreviated to ‘the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria’ or ‘the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1)’ for the purposes of this Constitution. This Constitution identifies the principles and rules governing the conduct of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria affairs and defines the powers of the constituent groups and the roles of the positions defined within. All other AGVAustralian Greens Victoria documents are subordinate to this Constitution with the exception of the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution. The Constitution seeks to maximise opportunities for productive cooperation between AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members and to provide protection for individual AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members and constituent groups. The Constitution requires the constituent groups of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria to: agree to the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution of the Greens, and to abide by this Constitution as well as to the National Constitutionthe Constitution of the Australian Greens of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, and to the proper decisions of the National Organisation; and support affirmative action and practise participatory, democratic and accountable internal decision-making processes. The Constitution further requires that the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and all its constituent groups have autonomy to make decisions relating to their own affairs, provided that these decisions remain compatible with the Constitution, the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution and the agreed policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do frameworks of the Greens.

The CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution is the basic document of agreement which defines the principles and aims of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626. As such, AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members and constituent groups should not publicly forward ideas at variance with the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution without calling into question their continued membership of, and status within, the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. To change the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution, an amendment must be supported in a plebiscite by at least75. per cent of eligible members of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 nationwide. For the result of such a plebiscite to be valid, at least51. per cent of members of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 must have participated.
documents.s: The CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution of the Greens

documents.t: The primary purposes of the Greens Party are: to further a vision of the world characterised by peace, social justice, grassroots participatory democracy and ecological sustainability; to make, publicise and strive to implement policies on national and global issues as described in the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution; to engage in education of both ourselves and the rest of the community, to raise awareness of the issues and concerns covered in the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution; to promote and assist other individuals, associations, organisations and community networks, working for the objectives of the Greens; to promote the development of and participate and communicate with the Green political movement both nationally and globally; to be a registered political partya political party registered under Commonwealth, state or territory law pursuant to the Commonwealth and Victorian Electoral Acts; to seek the election or appointment to public officean elected office in a council or parliament of people who are committed to the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution, principles, policies and objectives of the Greens; to encourage other political parties to adopt our policies and principles by electoral strategies and direction of voting preferences; to coordinate mutual support and joint actions on behalf of Greens Party Members; to carry out such tasks as the membership may from time to time delegate to the State body.

The Greens is a national confederation of State and territory parties. To facilitate smooth operations between the State and National Organisation, the State Constitution must remain broadly consistent and compatible with the National Constitutionthe Constitution of the Australian Greens. The Victorian National Delegates’ Convenor is responsible for co-ordinating the work of Victorian delegates to National Council and National Conference of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626. The Victorian National Delegates’ Convenor must be and remain one of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria delegates to both the National Council and the National Conference. State Council will enact a bylaw prescribing how this position is filled.

The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is committed to equal opportunity principles and the principle of women, men and gender diverse people having equal status within society. The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will initiate affirmative action, where appropriate, for underrepresented groups, in particular: 1. First Peoples; 2. women; and 3. gender-diverse people. At no time will any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member be discriminated against due to gender, age, race, ethnicity, class, religion, disability, sexuality, marital status, health status, or any other perceived or actual personal attribute.

The following terms have the specific meanings given below when they appear written in italic type within the State Constitution. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is the abbreviated term for the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 – Victoria, and is used along with the ‘Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1)’ throughout this Constitution to represent the body described in clause 1.1. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria MEMBERS are natural persons who have officially joined the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. AUSTRALIAN GREENS is the national confederation of State and territory-based Greens parties, of which the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is a member party. BANK ACCOUNT is any bank account, payment facility or other intermediary account with any external organisation designed for either the receipt, holding and/or payment of funds. BRANCH a constituent group of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria based on one or more Local Government Areas (subject to Schedule 1), consisting of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members registered to it by virtue of section 7 and/or clause 24.1(n). CHARTERThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution is the ‘CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution of the Greens’ which is the basic document of agreement which defines the principles and aims of the Greens. CONSTITUENT GROUPS are those Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) bodies (Branches, Regional Councils, State Council, State Executive, committees and working groups) which together make up the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. FINANCIAL YEARThe financial year of the Party is the year ending on 30 June. is the year ending on30. June. GREENS refers to any and/or all Greens parties, whether state or national. GREENS VICTORIA INC. is the incorporated body through which the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria conducts its business. NATIONAL CONSTITUTION is the constitution of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626. NATIONAL COUNCIL The Greens organisation based on national representation according to the National Constitutionthe Constitution of the Australian Greens. NATIONAL ORGANISATION is the organisation based on national representation according to the National Constitutionthe Constitution of the Australian Greens of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 as it meets either as National Council or National Conference, or when it makes a decision by national plebiscite or by its defined policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do-making processes. NATURAL PERSON is a legal term meaning an individual human being, as opposed to a **group, corporation or organisation. OFFICE BEARERS refers to the three mandatory office bearer positions of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, namely the Convenor, Secretary and Treasurer (these three positions are standard throughout the Greens organisations and the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria’s constituent groups), and an Assistant State Secretary as defined in this Constitution. OPPRESSIVE CONDUCT includes conduct that is unfairly prejudicial to, or unfairly discriminatory against, a Member (including in the Member’s capacity as a member of a committee); or contrary to the interests of the Members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; and includes a reference to engaging in conduct by refusing or failing to take action. OPTIONAL PREFERENTIAL SYSTEM (of voting) is a system of voting where the voter’s choice of candidates in a ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ and their choice of order of preference is indicated by placing the number one (1) next to the name of the most-preferred candidate and then numbering as many or as few further candidates as desired with consecutive higher integers to indicate the order of preference – e.g. 1 or 1, 2 or 1, 2, 3 etc. PROSCRIBED ORGANISATIONS are other political parties or the subordinate bodies of other political parties. A list of these proscribed organisations will be decided upon and published by the National Council of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626. PROPORTIONAL REPRESENTATION (PRParty Room) SYSTEM (of distributing votes) is the method of counting votes where a quota is calculated to determine the number of votes required to elect a candidate. The State Council will formulate bylaws to establish an appropriate PRParty Room system for internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria elections. STATE CONSTITUTION or CONSTITUTION is the Constitution of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, i.e. this document. STANDING COMMITTEES are committees established as such by or under this Constitution. STATE COUNCIL is the governing body of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, subject only to State Conference decisions and this Constitution, which coordinates organisational, administrative, financial, policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do and electoral matters for Victoria as a whole. STATE EXECUTIVE or EXECUTIVE means the State Executive described in Chapter 3.5. In this Constitution: biased means unable to bring an impartial and unprejudiced mind to the resolutiona proposal that was passed of the question under consideration; insolvent under administrationhas the meaning given in the Interpretation of Legislation Act 1984 has the same meaning as it has in the Interpretation of Legislation Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 1984; local councillor has the same meaning as councillor has in the Local Government Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 1989; represented person has the same meaning as it has in the Guardianship and Administration Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 1986.
In this chapter:

A member (the applicant) may make a misconduct allegation against a member (the respondent) by giving notice in writing of the following to, and only to, the Convenor of the Misconduct Panel or, if the allegation is made against the Convenor of the Misconduct Panel, to any other member of the Misconduct Panel: their name; the name of the respondent; a description of the actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 or acts of the respondent that are said to be misconduct; and a brief submission setting out why the applicant believes that actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 or those acts constitute misconduct. A member must not make a misconduct allegation in bad faith. A respondent may appoint any person to actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 on their behalf for the purposes of the misconduct allegation.

A member of the Misconduct Panel who receives a notice under clause 87.1 (the appointer) must: regarding so much of a misconduct allegation made against a member who is an applicant under clause 83.1, or any member appointed to actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 on their behalf under clause 83.5, in relation to the matter which is the subject of the application under clause 83.1— exercise their power under sub-clauses 2. and 3. only after the application under clause 83.1 is dealt with; and (ii) notify the applicant of the state of the misconduct allegation; if another misconduct allegation against the respondent is already being dealt with by another Sub-Panel—in writing assign the allegation to that Sub-Panel unless doing so would increase the effort or time required for the Misconduct Panel to deal with all of the allegations; or otherwise—in writing appoint a 3-member Sub-Panel (which may include themselves) to deal with the misconduct allegation. Subject to clause 8 8.3, a Sub-Panel must be made up of members of the Misconduct Panel.

The Sub-Panel must dismiss without consideration under clause 89.13(a)9. so much of a misconduct allegation that concerns an actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 or acts that are alleged to have occurred more than 180 days before the allegation was made except if: that part of the allegation was reinstated under clauses89. .15 or89. .16; or it decides that: that part of the allegation is of repeated similar conduct that continued into the 180 day period before the allegation was made; (ii) that part of the allegation relates to matters of a sexual nature; or (iii) exceptional circumstances warrant it not doing so. A misconduct allegation is under consideration from when it is made until all parts of it are either: dismissed; or found to be substantiated and a sanction imposed or not imposed. While a misconduct allegation is under consideration:
The Sub-Panel must, within four days of making a decision:

If a Sub-Panel makes a decision under clause 89.13(f), the next meeting of State Council must, in closed session, consider a proposal to impose the recommended sanction. State Council must decide to impose:

In this clause, application means an application under clause 83.1 to the Administrative Review Panel regarding a decision of either or both of a Sub-Panel under clause 89.13 or State Council under clause 91.2. An applicant, a respondent, the State Convenor or the State Secretary may make an application once a misconduct allegation is no longer under consideration. No other consideration or reconsideration (whether by review, appeal or otherwise) of the decisions made under this chapter is available under this Constitution. An application made more than 7 days after notification of the opportunity to appeal was sent must be dismissed by the Administrative Review Panel unless it decides that exceptional circumstances justify it not being dismissed. The remedies that the Administrative Review Panel may grant on an application are limited to:
