documents.t: The Convenor of the Misconduct Panel must make, and provide to all members, a Notice of Sanction if a sanction has been imposed, and all related misconduct allegations against the member are no longer under consideration and:

If a respondent’s membership ceases while a misconduct allegation against them is under consideration: the allegation must continue to be dealt with under this chapter as if their membership had not ceased; and any sanction imposed takes effect upon the respondent being re-admitted to AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership. Any person expelled from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria may only subsequently be re-admitted to AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership by the State Council. The State Executive or State Council may also resolve that a former member, whose conduct has been called into question and whose membership has ceased other than by expulsion, may only be admitted either by State Council, or with the approval of the State Executive. Subject to clause 94.5 below, should the State Council form the view that any conduct (including previous conduct of which it was not aware) of an endorsed AGVAustralian Greens Victoria candidate may damage, or has seriously damaged the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1), and that urgent action is required, the State Council will have the power to immediately expel or suspend that Member, provided the Member has been given, at least24. hours prior to the meeting which will consider the matter, a notice that: sets out the alleged conduct in question; and stipulates the time and place of the meeting; and

The Misconduct Panel is composed of 9 members appointed by State Council. The term of appointment of a member of the Misconduct Panel is 2 years. A member of the Misconduct Panel whose term of appointment to the Misconduct Panel expires whilst they are a member of a Sub-Panel remains a member of that Sub-Panel whilst it exists, including if a misconduct allegation (or part of one) is reinstated before it under clauses89. .15 or 16.. To be eligible to be appointed to and remain a member of the Misconduct Panel, a member:
State Council may make a bylaw that provides:

There will be an incorporated association (formed under the Associations Incorporation Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 1981 ) to actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 as trustee for the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria in all financial matters. The incorporated association will be known as The Greens Victoria Inc. The State Council and Branches will conduct all their financial transactions through The Greens Victoria Inc. As part of its charterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution, The Greens Victoria Inc. will hold in trust all funds and property belonging to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, in accordance with this Constitution. The State Office Bearers of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will automatically be nominated as Office Bearers of The Greens Victoria Inc. The State Council may nominate other persons with the relevant expertise to assist in the management of The Greens Victoria Inc. The State Council will decide on mechanisms by which AGVAustralian Greens Victoria finances are managed.

The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will have a Common Seal on which the name of The Greens Victoria Inc. will appear in legible characters. The Common Seal will not be used without the express written authority of the State Council and every use of the Seal will be recorded by the State Secretary. The Common Seal must only be affixed by the State Secretary and duly witnessed by another State Office Bearer. The Common Seal will be kept in the custody of the State Secretary.

The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is an organisation registered with both the Australian and Victorian Electoral Commissions, whereas the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is also a member party of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, a party also registered with the Australian Electoral Commission. For the purposes of Federal elections, the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria normally operates as a party member of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626. State Council may appoint a member to be one or more of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria’s:

The State Treasurer will be the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) Agent as defined in the Commonwealth Electoral Act19. 18, Part XX, Division 2. If the position of Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) Agent is vacant, the Registered Officer will assume the role of Acting Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) Agent until the position is filled.
documents.s: Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) Agent

documents.t: Each year the State Council will appoint an Auditor. The position of Auditor may be honorary, or the State Council may determine the sum of an honorarium. The Auditor will submit a written report to the State Council for presentation at the Annual State Conference, or at the earliest possible State Council if the report cannot be completed before the Annual State Conference. The Auditor will not be an AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Member and will be a qualified accountant. A copy of the Auditor’s report will be forwarded to the State Treasurer.

There will be an audit and finance committee, which will be responsible for ensuring the integrity of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1)’s financial reporting systems, including monitoring risk management systems and internal controls and compliance, and liaising with the external auditor and management.

AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members may at any time inspect the books and documents of The Greens Victoria Inc., by request to the State Secretary or other Office Bearer of the State Council. Despite this and the provisions of clauses 8.1(g),18. .13. and19. .12. of this Constitution, Standing Committees of the State Council and any other body established by this Constitution may, but only on reasonable grounds, designate any matter to be confidential in a particular case, and the bylaws may also prescribe, but only on reasonable grounds, that certain classes of documents or records shall remain confidential to certain Committees or persons, which shall always include the State Executive and, where it so determines, the State Council.

The funds of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria may be derived from joining fees, annual subscriptions, donations, fund- raising activities, grants, interest, public election funding, and any other sources approved by State Council. Substantial external funding received by the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will be itemised in a report which is open to public inspection. The monetary cut-off point below which no itemisation is required will be specified in the bylaws.

Subject to section64. , ‘The Greens Victoria Inc.’, and in consultation with the State Treasurer, State Council may raise funds and incur debts in the name of The Greens Victoria Inc. Subject to section64. , ‘The Greens Victoria Inc.’, and in consultation with the State Treasurer, a Branch of15. or more members may raise funds and incur debts in the name of The Greens Victoria Inc., up to a specified limit. Branches will not borrow funds from lending institutions or from any other source, without the prior approval of the State Treasurer.

The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria is not a partner of any of the other member bodies of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 and will not be liable for the acts or defaults of any of them. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members will not be liable to contribute towards the payment of the debts and liabilities or the costs, charges and expenses in winding up the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626.

AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members who, in acting on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria with written authority of the State Council, Branches or a constituent group, accept or incur any personal pecuniary liability, will be held indemnified against that personal liability in respect of such action.

The property and income of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will be applied solely towards promoting the principles and achieving the objectives of the Greens and no part of that property or income may be applied or otherwise distributed, directly or indirectly, except in good faith for that purpose.

The Constitution should be subject to comprehensive review at least every five years, with full consultation amongst the membership. Four members will be elected by State Council at the Annual State Conference to form the Constitution Review Panel. The purpose of the Constitution Review Panel is to ensure the Constitution is compliant with laws and that it functions effectively in the interests of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1). The powers of the Constitution Review Panel are to: receive and consider proposals for amendments to the Constitution; call for submissions from Members in respect of any proposal for constitutional change; take into account submissions from Members;

The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria will not be dissolved except by a resolutiona proposal that was passed of the full AGVAustralian Greens Victoria membership passed in a postal ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’, held in accordance with this Constitution and unless there are75. per cent or more

The costs of sending the specified number of allowed representatives or delegates to annual state or national conferences will be shared around the state. The costs of teleconferences and other communication means will be shared around the state when state co-ordination is discussed. The expenses of state-based working groups and the expenses of State Office Bearers and members of the State Council will be shared around the state. The expenses of national working groups, or individuals with national working groups, operating from Victoria, will be shared nationally.

Whereas at the time of the adoption of certain amendments to the Constitution which commenced in February20. 12, there were a number of Branches in existence whose geographic jurisdiction did not correspond to one or more Local Government Areahas the meaning given to the term municipal district in the Local Government Act 2020, the purpose of this Schedule is to: ensure that within such Local Government Areas (only), either those Branches may continue or other arrangements as provided for in this Schedule are given effect; and prescribe the representation of such Branches on State Council. The Local Government Areas referred to in clause 1 of this Schedule are the City of Greater Geelong, the Borough of Queenscliffe and the Shire of Yarra Ranges. The Branches referred to in clause 1 (being those which were in existence at the time of the amendments to the Constitution in February 20. 12 and still in existence at the time of the inclusion of this Schedule in the Constitution) are Geelong and District, Bellarine, Dandenong Ranges, Healesville and Upper Yarra. These are referred to in this Schedule respectively as ‘Schedule 1 LGAs’ and ‘Schedule 1 Branches.’ Notwithstanding the terms of the Constitution, but subject to this Schedule, each Schedule 1 Branch shall continue in existence and shall have the same geographic jurisdiction (or such expanded jurisdiction as State Council may determine, but only for the purpose of ensuring that each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria member within a Schedule 1 LGALocal Government Area is covered by the jurisdiction of a Schedule 1 Branch) unless and until that Branch votes to dissolve itself or lapses or is suspended in accordance with the Constitution and is not re-established within12. months. Should such a Branch vote to merge with another Branch it may only do so if it amalgamates with another Branch or Branches in the same Schedule 1 LGALocal Government Area; or otherwise such that the resultant merged Branch corresponds to one or more Local Government Areahas the meaning given to the term municipal district in the Local Government Act 2020. Where a Schedule 1 Branch exists whose jurisdiction does not correspond to one or more Local Government Area, the representation on State Council of the relevant Branches by Branch Representatives will be such that the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members in each Schedule 1 LGALocal Government Area shall, if it has at least15. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members, elect one Branch Representative to State Council (including to a casual vacancyincludes a vacancy caused by an office not being filled at an election), in accordance with any by law enacted by State Council, or in default of such a by law, by a postal ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of the relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members conducted at the same time as elections for regional representatives. Where the person or committee appointed by the State Executive is responsible for determining which Legislative Council region a Branch falls into for the purposes of State Council representation, Schedule 1 Branches which abut each other must all be assigned to the same Legislative Council region, which shall be the Legislative Council region that a plurality of members of the abutting Schedule 1 Branches reside within. Whereas certain functions, powers and responsibilities are vested in a Branch under clauses: 1.24. .1 5. (replacing a State Council representative); 2.24. .1 8. (endorsing local government candidates); 3.55. . 1 (Branches being local government campaign committees); 4.56. .4 1. (local government pre-selection); and 5.57. .1 (preferences in local government); in the case of Branches within or partly within Schedule 1 LGAs, State Council may enact by laws prescribing how such decisions may be made jointly by the relevant Schedule 1 Branches or by the members of those Branches. In default of such by laws any decision which would otherwise be made by a Branch corresponding to one or more Local Government Areahas the meaning given to the term municipal district in the Local Government Act 2020 may be made by concurrent decisions of all the relevant Branches.

The purpose of this Chapter is to regulate the formation and drafting of policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do for the political purposes of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. State Council may make bylaws to facilitate any element of the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do process outlined hereunder. Given that policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do is particularly scrutinised during an electoral campaign, it will normally be reviewed or developed in the period between elections. Reviews of current policies and development of new policies may be initiated by decision of State Council or by a petition supported by the signatures of at least 1 per cent or50. , whichever is the lesser, of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members. Policies which concern only one Branch area or region may be decided by an authorised Branch or Regional Council responsible for that area, and must be consistent with state policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do. Copies of all policies adopted by a Branch or Regional Council will be forwarded immediately to the State Secretary and to the convenor of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee. State policies will be formulated with the maximum participation of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members through the meeting procedures outlined in chapter 3.6, and should actively consider input from relevant

The Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee is a Standing Committee of State Council. It is responsible to State Council for the formulation and drafting of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do. The Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee is responsible for:
documents.s: The Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee

documents.t: The Convenor of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee will be elected by all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members by annual postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ (though if the position remains unfilled after the annual postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ for any reason, that position may be elected by all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members present at the Annual Conference or at a Special State Conference by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or, failing this consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so, by a secret ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members present), and will be a voting member of the State Executive and State Council. An individual who has served two consecutive terms as Convenor will not be eligible for re-election at the next election (but will in any case be eligible for subsequent elections), unless this provision is waived by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so decision of State Council. The position of Convenor of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee may be held on a job-share basis, in which case clauses15. .5,15. .6 and15. .7 shall apply as though ‘Office Bearers’ means ‘Convenors of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee’ and ‘Executive’ means ‘Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee’, and clause 15.9 will also apply. The Convenor of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee will:
documents.s: The Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Convenor

documents.t: Taking into account the advice of the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee, State Council will make bylaws regulating the process to be undertaken in formulating AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do. The bylaws will include, but not be limited to: determining the establishment, role and responsibilities of working groups to develop specific policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do areas; establishing a process which ensures adequate input into the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do process by AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members, Greens elected to public officean elected office in a council or parliament and external experts; and establishing a process for reaching a consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so position (as far as that is possible) on draft policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do which is developed for State Council approval.
documents.s: Formulation of Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do

documents.t: Subject to the appropriate notice periods and other requirements specified below, AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do may be approved by a consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so decision of State Council, or by a75. per cent majority vote of State Council, or by a75. per cent majority vote of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members by postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’. Where, at a State Council meeting, any policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do or part of a policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do is adopted, that policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do will become official policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do immediately. Notwithstanding clause 62.2, any whole or part of a policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do or proposed policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do will be subject to a postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of Members if: State Council determines that the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do or proposed policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do will be subject to a postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’; or within28. days of consideration by State Council, 1 per cent or50. (whichever is the lesser) of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members request in writing to the State Secretary that the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do or proposed policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do be subject to a postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members. The result of a postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ to determine policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do will be conclusive provided that20. per cent of the eligible AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members voted, and at least75. per cent of the valid votes cast are in favour, and that policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do will become official policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do immediately. If a postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ is to be conducted under clause 62.3, State Council will determine what is put to the Members, including the question or questions that fairly represent the diversity of views that have been expressed by Members at the State Council or State Conference. Where such questions include policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do proposals that are inconsistent in whole or in part with each other, and where both policies receive at least75. per cent of the valid votes cast, the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do that obtains the greatest support will be adopted. The State Council will not make any policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do decision which contradicts any current policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria approved by a ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members conducted as specified in clause 62.4, within the life of the current parliamentary or local government term.
documents.s: Adoption of Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do

documents.s: COUNTRY GREENS NETWORK TERMS OF REFERENCE

documents.t: To establish and build a network of Greens partyone of the member bodies of the Australian Greens members of the Northern, Western and Eastern Victoria Upper House regions.

To facilitate and properly resource party building in each of the country Upper House regions; To foster a supportive environment for the pre-selection of candidates in all country seats in Victoria; To establish a forum for policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do discussion and development with regard to interests, perspectives and issues relevant to people living in country Victoria; To seek representation of those interests, perspectives and issues in the Greens partyone of the member bodies of the Australian Greens platform; To establish a public presence in rural areas and regional centres that will allow country Victorians to engage with the Greens; To establish a coordinated media and public presence in country Victoria consistent with A.G.V. media guidelines; To set up I.T. infrastructure and support (website portal, bulletin boards, e lists etc) that facilitates networking across the rural Upper House regions, recognizing the connectivity constraints of country Victoria; To resource continuous campaigning in each of the rural Upper House regions; To provide a conduit between country Victorians and Green MPs.
The Network will be underpinned by the values evident in the Victorian Greens constitution, and meeting protocol.
Ongoing network

The Country Greens Network is a loose network of all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members residing in the rural Upper House regions with an Executive Committee comprising: A representative from each branch in the rural Upper House regions elected by that branch, if the branch chooses to elect a representative; The representative to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 Country Greens Working Group elected by the Committee from amongst all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members residing in the rural Upper House regions; and A convenor, an IT officer, and a Secretary elected by the Committee from its membership, or external. Executive group meets a minimum of quarterly (e.g. by email, teleconferencing or other means open to remote communities).

The office bearers are: Convenor, whose duties include: Convening meetings Ensuring the network sticks to these terms of reference Presenting an annual report to the network conference Providing a written annual report to State Conference, received by the State Secretary no less than 7 days prior to the Annual State Conference meeting on: current membership; meeting activity; progress on areas that are within the aims; and any reports from the representative to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 Country Greens Working Group. Providing a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken. I.T. Officer, whose duties include Compiling a contact list for the network Creating and maintaining the network portal website Keeping a current email list Secretary, whose duties will include: Arranging for minutes to be taken and the copy passed to State Secretary Work with IT officer to update website content Develop the use of social media for CGNCountry Greens Network Membership development with emphasis on connecting with CGNCountry Greens Network members where there are no branches.

Dates of all meetings will be determined by the current convenor in conjunction with ExecState Executive committee; The State Secretary will be advised of ALL meetings to be held; The minimum required number of meetings annually shall be 4; Notice of any meeting shall be advertised on the network email site; Attendance is open to all financial members of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, Victoria and attendees have speaking rights; The minimum reporting requirements are (a) Name of Network (b) Date of meeting (c) Persons in attendance (d) Decisions made Decision making – see Decision Making at Working Group Meetings

Open to interested financial party members residing within the Northern, Western or Eastern Victoria Upper House region boundaries; The State Convenor is an ex-officio member of this network, and the State Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do coordinator is an ex-officio member for all policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do discussions; The means of communication for the network shall be email and website; It is incumbent upon membership to inform themselves of meetings and keep abreast of developments; The email list/site shall contain all those financial members who wish to be on the list; The content of all emails will be non-confrontational, but constructive
To be approved by the Country Greens Network executive group responsible to the branches that form the network. No ability to incur debt or unfunded liabilities.
Public comment will be made through elected representatives, or members nominated by the Country Greens Network executive and subsequently appointed by State Council.

A minimum of one annual review will be made by State office bearers to consider the overall functioning and effectiveness of the network. A copy of the current terms of reference must be displayed on the internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria website. In the event that the it fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where it is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council may choose to dissolve the group.

Decisions shall be made in accordance with Section 48 of the party’s State Constitution, ‘Decision Making in Meetings’ as summarized below: Decisions will be made primarily by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so and a serious attempt at all times will be made towards achieving consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so. However, if disagreement persists, and a decision cannot be deferred, the question will be resolved by vote. A procedural question to this effect will be deemed to have been carried if it is supported by at least a 75% majority. Delegates’ abstentions may be recorded but will not count as a vote, either for or against. Voting by proxy is not allowed. When voting occurs it will be conducted by a show of hands. Voting of all members will be recorded.
BLAKGREENS VICTORIA – TERMS OF REFERENCE (Final Version 01 OCT 2019)
AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Australian Greens Victoria AGMAnnual General Meeting Annual General Meeting BGV BlakGreens Victoria QDMGQuick Decision Making Group Quick Decision Making Group

The name of the working group is BlakGreens Victoria (BGV). These terms of reference for the working group are written with proud acknowledgment of the 38 living First Nations in the colonial state of Victoria. We pay respect to our ancestors and warriors of the frontier wars, our elders and descendants of all First Nations in Victoria. We stand in solidarity for justice and empowerment for our First People. The sovereignty of this land was never ceded. This was, is and always will be First Nations Land.

BGV is a working group of the Australian Greens Victoria (AGVAustralian Greens Victoria) with the purposes of: Increasing membership in the Australian Greens Victoria of people from First People backgrounds; Supporting members with First People backgrounds to participate in Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 at all levels, from local, regional to national membership participation; and Serving as a forum for expert advice and consultation within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria on First Nations affairs and policies.

BGV will work to provide an authoritative voice within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria for members with First People backgrounds including, but not limited to: Advocating for First Nations representations within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and in local councils or parliaments of Australia; Advocating for training of members with First People backgrounds to enable them to participate in AGVAustralian Greens Victoria party processes; Informing the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria party bodies of First Nations affairs, including on campaigning and policies. In congruence with the CharterThe Charter of The Greens which is appended to the National Constitution of the Greens, BGV shall work to communicate, liaise and advocate for First People communities in Victoria, when requested by these communities, elders or delegates, on issues significantly impacting or of significant importance to these communities.

BGV shall comprise AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members who identify themselves with First Nations heritage. 7. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members of non-First People background are welcome to participate as supporters or co-opted members of BGV, when invited by a BGV member. Co-opted members are unable to exercise a vote or block a consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so.

BGV shall consist of a core group of office-bearers that include the following positions, with each role ideally shared by two people of different genders: Convenor / Co-Convenors; and Secretary / Co-Secretaries; with Treasurer / Co-Treasurers (if BGV holds funds). Members of BGV shall elect office-bearers from their number annually, as agreed by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so by the working group at an annual general meeting (AGMAnnual General Meeting). In support of office-bearer roles as per clause 9, BGV may elect at the AGMAnnual General Meeting two sets of office-bearers for each role to rotate in 6 monthly rotations to share the duties of the roles. BGV members shall nominate their Victorian delegate to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 First Nations Committee from their membership. Should any office-bearer position becomes vacant before an AGMAnnual General Meeting, it shall be filled if possible at the next BGV meeting.

The Convenor(s) shall be responsible, among other things, to: convene meetings; ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and be the main contact person for BGV. The Secretary(ies) shall be responsible, among other things, to: provide notice of meetings; prepare and distribute meeting minutes; prepare and distribute meeting agendas; and keep a record of all proceedings. The Treasurer(s) will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions. If there is no Treasurer, the Secretary upkeeps the responsibility of the Treasurer.

BGV shall meet at least once every 3 months. The quorum for general meetings is 3 members, one of which must be an office-bearer. Decisions will be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so. So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time, and venue or electronic method for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least 3 days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12 hours notice if 3 members, one of which must be an office-bearer, agree that it is necessary. Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members in advance of each meeting, and members provided with an agenda for that meeting and unconfirmed minutes for the previous meeting. The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and confirmed minutes are to be sent to the State Secretary.

BGV may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of BGV. QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office-bearers and two other members. QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so by a quorum of 3 members. All QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next BGV meeting for ratification. A written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.

All records of the working group proceedings shall be kept by the Secretary of BGV, and shared with the State Secretary as soon as practical (ideally within 14 days). If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 14 days.
AGV Australian Greens (Victoria) QDMG Quick Decision Making Group MWG Multicultural Working Group CALD Cultural and Linguistically Diverse
The name of the committee is the Multicultural Working Group.

MWG is a state wide group of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria with the purposes of: a) increasing CALD membership in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria; b) increasing CALD participation in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria at all levels; c) increasing support for the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria within CALD communities.

MWG has general responsibility for working towards strengthening opportunities in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria for people from diverse cultural backgrounds. MWG will operate as a forum for consultation within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria on multicultural issues, including AGVAustralian Greens Victoria multicultural policies. MWG will work to ensure that CALD communities are given an effective voice within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. This work can include, but is not limited to: a) advocating for or assisting in the implementation of CALD sensitive election policies; b) facilitating the establishment of CALD community contacts and relationships; and/or c) advocating for multicultural election campaigns and targeted CALD campaigns.

MWG will comprise any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members interested in multicultural and CALD issues. Members of the MWG shall annually elect office-bearers from their number at an annual general meeting. They shall include a Convenor, a Secretary and a Treasurer Should any office bearer position become vacant, it shall be filled if possible at the next MWG meeting. The MWG may elect co-office bearers. A member of the MWG cannot hold multiple office bearer positions within the MWG.

The Convenor shall be responsible, among other things, to: a) convene meetings; b) ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and c) be the main contact person for MWG. The Secretary shall be responsible, among other things, to: a) provide notice of meetings; b) prepare and distribute meeting minutes; c) prepare and distribute meeting agendas; and d) keep a record of all proceedings. The Treasurer will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions. The Treasurer will be a signatory, with the Convenor and Secretary of MWG, for the MWG bank account. Two out of three office bearers can authorise financial transactions.

MWG shall meet at least bimonthly. The quorum for general meetings is 50% of office bearers and four members. Decisions will be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so. So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time and venue for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least five days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12 hours notice if at least four of the members, including one office bearer, agree that it is necessary. Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members, and an agenda will be distributed in advance of each meeting. Unconfirmed minutes will be distributed by the Secretary within five days of each meeting to all members and to others who were present. The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and copies are to be sent to state office.

MWG may establish a Quick Decision Making Group for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of MWG. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in part 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows: a) QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and one other member; b) the QDMGQuick Decision Making Group quorum shall be three members; c) QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so; d) all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; and e) a written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.

All records of the proceedings of MWG shall be kept by the Secretary. If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 7 days. MWG will provide State Council - immediately following the conclusion of a general election campaign - with a written report of its campaigning. MWG will provide Annual State Conference with a written report of its: a) current membership; b) meeting activity; and c) progress on areas that are within the purpose and objectives.

**J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Terms Of Reference (Endorsed by State Executive, 17. August 2017) (Amended by State Council, 6. July 2019) (Amended by Membership Engagement Committee, 8. June 2020) ABBREVIATIONS AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 (Victoria) QDMGQuick Decision Making Group Quick Decision Making Group J-GreensJewish Greens Jewish Greens
The name of the working group shall be the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC).

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall promote the alignment of progressive Jewish community with that of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, and support opportunities for the membership and participation of Jewish people within the Greens.

Membership of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be open to all financial paid up Jewish members of the Australian Greens Victoria and to non-Jewish members of the party who support this group. 3.1. The J-Greens (VIC) shall encourage attendance and participation by Greens aligned Jewish citizens who shall hold non-voting member status, subject to the consensus decision of the Members of the Meeting to which they are attending. 3.2. Non-voting member shall be excluded from any matters which are subject to party confidentiality. 3.3. Member status may be revoked and such revocation may take place by special majority of wither existing members or, when there is urgency, the QDMG will make a immediate determination which subsequently will be confirmed in the following meeting. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall annually elect a Convenor, Treasurer and Secretary at an Annual General Meeting. The group may elect co-office bearers. In the event that the group elects to have co-office bearers, it is desirable that at least one of these identify as a woman. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may elect additional office bearers when required. Should any office bearer position become vacant, it shall be filled by a vote of all members present at the next J- Greens (VIC) meeting. The Secretary will maintain a list of current members of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) for the purposes of advertising and conducting meetings, and conducting ballots to elect office-bearers. A member of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) cannot hold multiple office bearer positions within the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC).

The Convenor or Co-Convenors shall be responsible, among other things, to: a)convene meetings; b)ensure meetings are adequately facilitated; and c)be the main contact person for J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC). The Secretary or Co-Secretaries shall be responsible, among other things, to: a)provide notice of meetings; b)prepare and distribute meeting minutes; c)prepare and distribute meeting agendas; and d)keep a record of all proceedings. The Treasurer will be responsible for all records of financial decisions and transactions. The Treasurer will be responsible for ensuring the J-GreensJewish Greens adheres to all relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria By-laws regarding financial governance, including those relating to ethical review of donations. The Treasurer will be a signatory, with the Convenor or Co-Convenors and Secretary or Co-Secretaries of J- Greens (VIC), for the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) bank account. Two out of three office bearers must authorise financial transactions. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall offer access to an reference experts group to give advice on Jewish matters during normal Parliamentary business, during elections, on election strategy and to all elected representatives. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may work with members, branches, working groups and all levels of the Greens to promote effective means of engagement with the Jewish community. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may develop resources, provide training and mentorship to elected representatives and Greens spokespeople about Jewish issues, and the way local Victorian issues can be deeply affected by Israel & Palestinian affairs. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall support other groups and bodies within the confederation of Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 to share and develop multicultural awareness.

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria State Treasurer to open and operate a bank account. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with a budget that has been ratified by State Council. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Convenor and Treasurer will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) member may request funding for activities The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Convenor and Treasurer are responsible for acquittal in co-ordination with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer.

J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) meetings will be conducted in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria meeting procedures. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall meet at least once per quarter, either in person or by phone or videoconference. Valid meetings of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be those advertised to the group’s membership in advance and attended by at least five J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) members, including at least one convenor. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) members and its office bearers shall be bound by the Membership Code of Conduct. Any decisions made by meetings of the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary within ten days of the meeting. Decisions will be made by a serious at consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so at all times (as described part 48. of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution). So far as is practicable and possible, each meeting will set a date, time and venue for the next meeting. Where the date has not been set, or must be changed, the Secretary shall advertise the date, time and venue at least five days ahead. However, an urgent meeting may be called with no less than 12. hours notice if at least four of the members, including one office bearer, agree that it is necessary. Notice of meetings shall be provided to all members, and an agenda will be distributed in advance of each meeting. Unconfirmed minutes will be distributed by the Secretary within five days of each meeting to all members and to others who were present. The confirmation of previous minutes will be considered at each meeting, and copies are to be sent to state office The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall manage a secure online forum (such as Facebook) for members and observers that has the following purpose: To provide an avenue for progressing matters related to Jewish Greens Victoria’s mission to “​ promote the alignmentof progressive Jewish community with that of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626, and support opportunities for the membershipand participation of Jewish people within the Greens ​.” Posts, discussions, and comments should stick to matters relevant to this mission. The convenor holds responsibility of removing any items which depart or distract from furthering our mission with approval of QDMGQuick Decision Making Group.

J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC). It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in parts 50-55. of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows: QDMGQuick Decision Making Group membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and two ordinary other member; the QDMGQuick Decision Making Group quorum shall be three members; QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions must be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so; all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; and a written record shall be kept of all QDMGQuick Decision Making Group decisions.

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) is an ongoing Working Group. In the event that the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where the J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 Victoria may choose to dissolve the group.

The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on: a)current membership; b)meeting activity; and c)progress on areas that are within the purpose. The J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) Secretary must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary at the next available meeting.

All records of the proceedings of J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) shall be kept by the Secretary. If there is a change of Secretary, all records will be passed on within 7. days. J-GreensJewish Greens (VIC) will provide State Council – immediately following the conclusion of a general election campaign – with a written report of its campaigning.

documents.t: The name of the group shall be Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Working Group on Climate and Energy, which may be abbreviated to the Climate and Energy PWGPolicy Working Group (PWGPolicy Working Group).

It is the purpose of the PWGPolicy Working Group, in co-operation with the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee and as per the State Council approved policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do processes, to: a) develop and review policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do in the area of climate and energy policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do, and all aspects of these policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do areas, during the four-yearly substantive policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do review; b) monitor developments in its policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area(s), and recommend further variation to policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do as necessary; c) provide support to elected representatives and other spokespersons of the Greens, at their request; d) provide interpretation advice to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee on any question relating to the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area(s); e) actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 as a forum for members of the party to discuss issues in all aspects of the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area with the view of engaging members in the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do review process, engaging and informing members through discussion on interesting aspects of the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area, and providing support in the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area(s) for AGVAustralian Greens Victoria campaigns; and f) ensure that internal members-only discussions, including online forums, follow Greens safe-meeting practices. While the PWGPolicy Working Group does not have the responsibility for developing or implementing political strategy in the policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do area(s), or implementing specific initiatives, action plans or campaigns, these will be developed in consultation with the PWGPolicy Working Group where time permits.

The PWGPolicy Working Group will consult, as relevant and appropriate, with: a) the Policy Committee; b) constituent groups of the AGV; c) comparable Greens groups in other states and territories, the federal party, and international Greens groups; and d) other individuals with expertise or interest in the policy area. The Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee or State Council may request a report or research on any policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do matter within its area, at any time during the life of the PWGPolicy Working Group.
The PWGPolicy Working Group will commence operations when endorsed by the State Council meeting. The PWGPolicy Working Group is an ongoing working group.

Any financial members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria shall be eligible to stand for election to the PWGPolicy Working Group. State Council will elect eight PWGPolicy Working Group members annually from among all the members of the party. In addition, the parliamentary portfolio holder or spokesperson shall be a member of the PWGPolicy Working Group, and a local councillor selected by the local council representatives shall be added to the PWGPolicy Working Group. Where an extraordinary vacancy exists after an election has been held, PWGPolicy Working Group members may be appointed by approval of the State Council. Members have an obligation to actively participate in and contribute to the development or review of a policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do. A membership attendance list will be kept and registered with the State Secretary. Attendance and participation at meetings, as per meeting procedures below, is open to all members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. A PWGPolicy Working Group member will cease to be a member following absence from three consecutive meetings without notice, provided that the Convener may grant special leave of absence from meetings of the PWGPolicy Working Group to any member.

Members of the PWGPolicy Working Group shall annually elect from among themselves a Convener and Secretary. Where an extraordinary vacancy exists, an office bearer may by appointed by agreement of the PWGPolicy Working Group.

The PWGPolicy Working Group shall meet at least once per quarter, either in person or remotely. Notice of meetings will be advertised in advance through the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria e-bulletin, and per email to branch secretaries and members registered with the PWGPolicy Working Group. A quorum of any meeting of the PWGPolicy Working Group shall be at least half of PWGPolicy Working Group members. A meeting agenda will be provided to all PWGPolicy Working Group members and other AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members registered with the PWGPolicy Working Group prior to the meeting, and will be confirmed at the beginning of the meeting. Actions agreed and decisions made at a previous meeting will be taken as ‘not for further discussion’, unless a specific agenda item with a written proposal is forwarded to the Convener prior to the meeting. Decisions are generally made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so of all present at a meeting. However, in the event that consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so cannot be reached, a 75% majority of PWGPolicy Working Group members present can be taken as the decision.

A list of decisions made by the PWGPolicy Working Group will be minuted and distributed to members of the PWGPolicy Working Group and to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee. The Convener will keep the State Council and Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee informed of progress and activities as appropriate, with an annual written report on the group’s activities. The Convener must respond to any written correspondence from the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Convener or State Secretary. In the event that the PWGPolicy Working Group fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where the PWGPolicy Working Group is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council may choose to dissolve the group. The PWGPolicy Working Group shall not make any public statements without the prior approval of the relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria spokesperson.

Any agreed recommendations for policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do changes by the PWGPolicy Working Group are to be presented to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee for review and presentation to State Council for ratification. Whether the recommendations have been agreed by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or by the standard 75% vote shall be indicated to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee.

The Convener will keep the State Council and Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee informed of progress and activities as appropriate, with an annual written report on the group’s activities. The Convener must respond to any written correspondence from the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Convener or State Secretary. In the event that the PWGPolicy Working Group fails to meet its minimum meeting and reporting requirements, or in any instance where the PWGPolicy Working Group is seen to be breaching party rules, the State Council may choose to dissolve the group. The PWGPolicy Working Group shall not make any public statements without the prior approval of the relevant AGVAustralian Greens Victoria spokesperson.

Any agreed recommendations for policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do changes by the PWGPolicy Working Group are to be presented to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee for review and presentation to State Council for ratification. Whether the recommendations have been agreed by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or by the standard 75% vote shall be indicated to the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee.
