State Executive​ The State Executive is responsible for overseeing the day-to-day management of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1), subject to State Council direction. It is subordinate to and responsible to State Council. The State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, State Secretary, Assistant State Secretary, State Treasurer, the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee established under this Constitution, and seven general members. The State Convenor, State Secretary, State Treasurer and the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee will be elected in accordance with the procedures set out for each of them in this Constitution (see sections16. ,54. and60. ). The general members of the State Executive will be elected annually by and from the members of State Council, in accordance with the relevant bylaws, such that: three general members are elected for one year terms (except at the20. 15 election only, where five general members will be elected); and two general members are elected for two year terms. Casual vacancies for general member positions which fall more than one month before the expiry of the term will be filled by State Council from among its members for the remainder of the relevant term. 5. The State Executive will have all the general powers of State Council, subject to such conditions as the State Council may determine, other than: 1. the power to make, repeal or amend policy; 2. the power to adopt an annual or like budget; 3. the power to appoint members to the Administrative Review Panel and Misconduct Panel; and 4. the powers under clauses76. .5,76. .7 and91. . 6. The State Executive will meet as often as required, but must meet at least once every month when the State Council is not meeting, except in December and January. The quorum for a meeting of State Executive will be the next integer greater than half the number of voting members of the State Executive for the time being, including the occupants of not less than two of the Office Bearer positions. For the purpose of determining a quorum, not more than one of the Secretary or Assistant Secretary may be counted. 7. State Executive will require its decisions to be ratified by the State Council at the earliest opportunity, provided that the failure or refusal of State Council to ratify any decision by the State Executive will not transfer from the AGV to any member of the Executive any liability for actions taken in good faith, nor will it void any action taken in consequence of any Executive decision so taken prior to the State Council meeting in which the decision is considered. 8. The State Executive has a responsibility to supervise and co-ordinate the activities of the Standing Committees of State Council and to ensure the integration of the work of those committees, but will not have the power to direct the Standing Committees.

The State Executive is responsible for overseeing the day-to-day management of the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1), subject to State Council direction. It is subordinate to and responsible to State Council. The State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, State Secretary, Assistant State Secretary, State Treasurer, the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee established under this Constitution, and seven general members. The State Convenor, State Secretary, State Treasurer and the convenors of the Victorian Campaign Committee and the Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Steering Committee will be elected in accordance with the procedures set out for each of them in this Constitution (see sections16. ,54. and60. ). The general members of the State Executive will be elected annually by and from the members of State Council, in accordance with the relevant bylaws, such that: three general members are elected for one year terms (except at the20. 15 election only, where five general members will be elected); and two general members are elected for two year terms. Casual vacancies for general member positions which fall more than one month before the expiry of the term will be filled by State Council from among its members for the remainder of the relevant term.

Notice of Meetings and Elections​ Postal and/or electronic notices will be provided to Members, to: 1. effect postal ballots and the sending of related ballots papers; 2. provide notice of State Conferences; 3. notify relevant AGV Members of any meeting called to establish a Branch; and such notice, as defined and specified in the bylaws, will be given to all Members entitled to attend such AGV meetings. 2. To facilitate maximum participation in decision-making, AGV meetings should be scheduled, as far as is practicable, so that: 1. Branch meetings precede State Council meetings; 2. A State Council meeting should be held no later than 2 weeks prior to a National Council meeting; 3. A meeting of each working group should be held no later than 2 weeks before a meeting of the body which established the working group. Decision Making in Meetings​ Decisions at all meetings of AGVAustralian Greens Victoria constituent groups will be made primarily by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so, and a serious attempt at all times will be made towards achieving consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so. Sufficient time will be allowed for discussion of different views, including provision for non-decision making meetings. Except where this Constitution requires a decision to be made by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so only, if, after a reasonable period of time, disagreement persists and a decision should not be deferred, the question of moving to a vote on a substantive motion will be resolved by a vote. The procedural question to this effect will be deemed to have been carried if it is supported by at least a75. percent majority. A substantive motion carried by vote, unless provided for elsewhere in the Constitution, requires at least a75. per cent majority of votes cast. Abstentions may be recorded but will not count as a vote, either for or against. When voting occurs, it will be conducted by a show of hands, except in the case of contested elections which will be determined by a ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’. Voting of all members of the group will be recorded. Voting by proxy will be allowed at meetings of constituent groups if specifically allowed by the bylaws. A motion regarding a procedural question is carried if a majority of valid votes are in favour of the motion. Abstentions do not count as a vote, either for or against. For the purposes of this clause, a procedural question includes proposals deemed to be procedural questions under Standing Orders issued by the State Council as a bylaw. Notwithstanding the provisions of clause 48.5, a procedural motion to: 1. put a substantive motion to a vote; or 2. suspend the operation of the Standing Orders; will require at least a75. per cent majority of votes cast. 7. All AGV meetings and processes should ensure maximum participation of all involved, including by using small group discussions, subcommittees or working parties where appropriate. 8. All meetings of the AGV will be open to all AGV Members and invited members of the general public. At meetings of constituent groups consisting of elected representatives or delegates, the degree of participation of non-representatives/delegates can be constrained as detailed elsewhere in this Constitution as well as at the discretion of the meeting facilitator/convenor. 49 Decision Making through Postal or Electronic Ballots 1. A constituent group meeting may decide to poll relevant AGV Members through a postal or electronic ballot (to be funded by the constituent group). For the results of the ballot to be valid, a minimum of10. per cent of the AGV members polled must have participated in the ballot. For a motion to succeed it must be approved by at least75. percent of the valid votes cast. 2. Provision will be made available for important or contentious issues for the AGV to be resolved by postal or electronic ballot of all Members, and will be convened if initiated by10. % of individual AGV Members. For the results of the plebiscite to be valid, a minimum of10. per cent of AGV Members must have participated in the plebiscite. For a motion to succeed it needs to be approved by at least75. per cent of the valid votes cast. 3. State Council must decide on how the motions will be put on the ballot paper, as well as how supporting and opposing arguments will be made available to Members with the ballot paper. 4. When an electronic ballot is held, State Council must make adequate alternate voting arrangements for eligible Members who are not readily able to access the relevant electronic means. 5. Postal or electronic votes will be counted by the Returning Officer appointed by the State Council. 6. State Council may make further provision for the manner of conducting electronic or postal ballots in a bylaw. Quick Decision Making​ Any Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) body of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria may establish and (at each year’s AGMAnnual General Meeting) elect members to a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) comprised of members of that Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) body, to facilitate the making of urgent decisions. A casual vacancyincludes a vacancy caused by an office not being filled at an election may be filled from time to time. The functions and powers of a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) are as follows: 1. The QDMG will make decisions for the Party body regarding any matter of such urgency that it must be resolved before the next scheduled meeting of the Party body; 2. Whilst it is the Convenor who is normally required to attempt to contact all QDMG members, if necessary, any member of the QDMG can call the meeting. 3. The composition of the Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) is as follows: 1. The QDMG for the State Executive will comprise the State Convenor, the State Secretary, the State Treasurer and three persons appointed by and from the other members of the State Executive; 2. For all other Party bodies, the QDMG will comprise any two of that Party body’s Convenor, Secretary, and Treasurer (if it has one), and two other persons elected from the other members of the Party body; 3. quorum will be four decision-making members of the State Executive’s QDMG, or three members for any other Party body’s QDMG. 4. Procedures for the Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) include the following: 1. The QDMG will meet only as often as essential; 2. The QDMG may meet face to face or by teleconference, or by electronic communication. In emergencies, the QDMG may simply engage in telephone consultation; 3. In matters relating to particular regions or issues, the QDMG will consult where possible with constituent groups or Party Members who may be directly affected by the decision; 4. The QDMG’s decisions will be made by consensus only. 5. The Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) must keep a written record of any decisions made and present it to the next meeting of its Party body. 6. Decisions of a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMG) take effect immediately. If a decision of a QDMG is not ratified by the conclusion of the next quorate meeting of its Party body, the decision lapses and, to the maximum extent possible, is to be taken to have never been made.

The name of the group shall be the Queer Greens Victoria (QGVQueer Greens Victoria).

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be open to all members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria who identify as LGBTIQA+ and support the empowerment, equal opportunities, rights, safety, economic independence and self-determination of all LGBTIQA+ people within an intersectional framework. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Members who do not identify as LGBTIQ may actively participate in the QGVQueer Greens Victoria but may not vote, block consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or be office bearers. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall annually elect a Convenor, Secretary, and Treasurer at an AGMAnnual General Meeting. The working group may elect co-office bearers for any of these positions. In the event that the group elects to have co-office bearers, it is desirable that at least one of these not identify as a cisgender male. If nominating for a shared position, the nominees must nominate as a joint ticket. The annual election of office bearers may be done by either of: (a)attendance election by either of consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or paper ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ at a QGVQueer Greens Victoria AGMAnnual General Meeting; or (b)postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of all eligible and registered QGVQueer Greens Victoria members. QGVQueer Greens Victoria may elect additional office bearers when required. Casual Vacancyincludes a vacancy caused by an office not being filled at an election Elections of Office Bearers may be done by either of: (a)attendance election by either of consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’; or (b)postal or electronic ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of all eligible and registered QGVQueer Greens Victoria members.

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall serve as a forum for the engagement of LGBTIQA+ people and their allies in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and support the empowerment, equal opportunities, rights, safety, economic independence and self- determination of all LGBTIQA+ within an intersectional framework.

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall promote and facilitate the involvement of LGBTIQA+ people within an intersectional framework in the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and local branches. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall encourage and grow membership of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria within LGBTIQA+ communities and support LGBTIQA+ members to take roles of responsibility within the party. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may advocate in the interests of LGBTIQA+ Victorians within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria and across the broader community, and generate awareness of the issues facing LGBTIQA+ people and their families in Victoria and the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall ensure that the human rights of LGBTIQA+ people and families are protected and advanced within AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policies. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may contribute to AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do development within the scope of any policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do development process agreed to by the State Council. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may provide information on issues facing LGBTIQA+ people to elected AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members and support the delivery and implementation of policies relevant to LGBTIQA+ people. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may assist with or coordinate electoral or other campaigns that are consistent with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do or decisions of the Victorian Campaign Committee. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may fundraise for and support the election of LGBTIQA+ candidates at elections, consistent with decisions of the Victorian Campaign Committee.

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria State Treasurer to open and operate a bank account. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with an agreed budget or proposal agreed to at a QGVQueer Greens Victoria meeting. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria Treasurer in consultation with the QGVQueer Greens Victoria Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any QGVQueer Greens Victoria member may request funding for activities.

QGVQueer Greens Victoria may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria working group shall meet at least four times a year, either in person or via electronic means. Valid meetings of the QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be those advertised to the group’s members up to two weeks prior to the meeting date with a quorum of six QGVQueer Greens Victoria members, but the quorum must include at least one QGVQueer Greens Victoria Office Bearer, unless all Office Bearer positions are vacant. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so. Any decisions made by meetings of the QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary and QGVQueer Greens Victoria members within ten days of the meeting. QGVQueer Greens Victoria members are expected to abide by social media guidelines as outlined on the relevant platform and guided by AGVAustralian Greens Victoria bylaws around the use of social media.

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria working group will establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) of QGVQueer Greens Victoria members for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of QGVQueer Greens Victoria. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in clause 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution.
The QGVQueer Greens Victoria is an ongoing Working Group.

The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on: (a)current membership; (b)meeting activity; and (c) progress on any areas that are within the purpose and roles. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria Convenor/s must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary. The QGVQueer Greens Victoria shall provide a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken.

The name of the group shall be the Victorian Greens Women’s Network (VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network).

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be open to all members of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 (Victoria) (AGVAustralian Greens Victoria) who identify as women. AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members who do not identify as women are permitted to attend VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network meetings, conferences, and events as allies and observers (at the discretion of the office bearers), but may not vote, block consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or be office bearers. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall annually elect a Convenor, Secretary, a Representative to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 Women’s Working Group and a Treasurer. Office Bearers will be elected by members present at the Annual General Meeting or, failing consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so being reached, they will be elected by secret ballota secret ballot that uses a single transferable vote quota-preferential voting system, allows the option of not allocating further preferences, uses Robson Rotation, and provides an option of voting to ‘Seek Further Candidates’ of all members present at the Annual General Meeting. When necessary, a Returning Officer will be elected to supervise the conduct of ballots. The group may elect co-office bearers for any of these positions. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may elect additional office bearers when required. An office bearer may be removed by consensusthe circumstance in which no member of the party body who is in attendance objects to the proposal being passed, having been given the opportunity to do so or a two-thirds majority vote by the members of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network.

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall serve as a network, forum and social space for members of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, Greens voters and those who are aligned with Greens issues who are committed to women’s empowerment and gender equality. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will promote and advocate for solutions to address structural issues that impede women, especially marginalised women, from participating fully in electoral politics and free and fair debate within party structures. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will highlight and advocate for gender equality and women’s rights in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do and within an intersectional and feminist framework, promoting respect for women and their equal participation in social, working and economic life. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the election of women candidates into leadership and elected representative positions at all three levels of government, and to internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria leadership roles. In particular, the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the election of people who have experienced intersectional discrimination.

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall work to achieve equal representation of women in elected positions, internally and externally. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will advocate for systemic reform through measures such as affirmative action in accordance with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria constitution and best practice. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will function as a network to connect people working towards women's empowerment and gender equality through forums, meetings, training and social events. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will advocate for a gender lens on all AGVAustralian Greens Victoria policies and practices to support and underpin social and economic equality for women. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will support the preselection and election of female candidates for all three levels of government through mentoring, training, information sessions and support, opportunities to volunteer for women candidates, and the opportunity to meet and connect with elected officials. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network will liaise with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria state representative on women’s issues where possible to advance the work of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network in parliament and the public. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall work to raise awareness within and outside the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria of the role of intersectionality in the oppression of women, and to actively redress the impacts of multiple oppressions by supporting women who have experienced intersectional discrimination to take on leadership roles, including as candidates, office bearers, council members and other representatives.

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may make arrangements with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer to open and operate a bank account. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may only expend funds in accordance with an agreed budget. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Treasurer in consultation with the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network member may request funding from the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network office bearers. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Treasurer in consultation with the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor is responsible for acquittal in coordination with the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Treasurer.

VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network meetings will be conducted in accordance with AGVAustralian Greens Victoria meeting procedures. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may operate an internal AGVAustralian Greens Victoria email list. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall meet at least six times per year, either in person or via electronic means. Valid meetings of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be those advertised to the group’s members at least 7 days in advance and attended by at least five VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members including at least one office bearer of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network network. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall not make decisions on behalf of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria, except when delegated by State Council to do so. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members and participants at meetings and events shall be bound by the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Membership Code of Conduct. Any decisions made by meetings of the VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall be minuted and sent to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary within ten days of the meeting. VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network members are expected to abide by social media guidelines as outlined on the relevant platforms.

VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network may establish a Quick Decision Making Group (QDMGQuick Decision Making Group) for instances where urgent decisions need to be made before the next scheduled meeting of VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network. It shall operate in accordance with the provisions set out in part 50 of the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Constitution, the main points of which are as follows: a)QDMG membership shall consist of any two of the office bearers and two other members; b)the QDMG quorum shall be three members; c)QDMG decisions must be made by consensus; d)all QDMG decisions shall have immediate effect, but be put to the next meeting for ratification; and e)a written record shall be kept of all QDMG decisions.
The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network is an ongoing Working Group.

The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall provide a written report to each AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Annual State Conference on: a)current membership; b)meeting activity; c)progress on areas that are within the purpose and roles; and d)any reports from the Representative to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 Women’s Working Group. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network Convenor/s must respond to any written correspondence from the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Convenor and/or Secretary. The VGWNVictorian Greens Women's Network shall provide a written report to State Council immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken.

**Established: 1 June 2019 Modified by State Executive: 15 August 2019 Modified by Membership Engagement Committee: 6 April 2020 Modified by Membership Engagement Committee: 8 June 2020 Name The name of the Working Group shall be the Victorian Greens (VGVictorian Greens) People with Disabilities Working Group (VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group).

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group aims to: Build spaces and support networks to be a welcoming organisation for people with disabilities; Help the Greens continue to lead on disability issues; and Create a mechanism to work with VGVictorian Greens Policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do Committee to enrich all policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do areas with the knowledge and expertise of members with disabilities about how it may impact people with disabilities.

Voting members of the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group shall be members of the Victorian Greens who identify as a person with a disability, have a disability or disabilities or are disabled. In the case of voting member with decision-making or communicative disability, they may be assisted by supporters or representatives as currently defined in “Equality, Capacity and Disability in Commonwealth Laws.” Supporters or representatives shall be in attendance only when the voting member is present. A VGVictorian Greens Office Staff Member will be a nonvoting member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group. Two members of the VGVictorian Greens Office Bearers Group will be non-voting members of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group. A member of the state Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) Room or their representative may be a non-voting member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group recognises the strength in diversity and intersectionality and welcomes input and participation from people with disabilities who are in other marginalised groups, including but not limited to women, people who identify as LGBTIQ, people from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds, and people from regional and rural areas. Experts, carers and allied health professionals may be invited to actively participate within VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group activities, but non-members of the Victorian Greens may not be a member of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group or be afforded voting or blocking rights. Parents of children with a disability are encouraged to join but would not have voting or blocking rights unless the issue under discussion related specifically to children with disabilities such as education or early intervention.

VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will elect office bearers on an annual basis or whenever a vacancy arises through accessible voting platforms such as email/online ballots. The office bearers include a Convenor, Secretary, Delegate to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 People with Disabilities Working Group and Technical Assistant. These roles may be shared by up to two people. All office bearers shall be voting members, where a voting member has nominated for the position. If no voting members nominate for a specific role then it may be opened to non-voting members. Members of Parliament and state office bearers cannot be office bearers of VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group. The duties of the Convenor comprise: Ensuring that the appropriate notice of meeting, agenda and motions on notice are provided in good time; Ensuring that the business of each meeting is properly addressed; Presenting an Annual Report to the Annual State Conference; Contacting other available members to convene a quick response to urgent and pressing political matters; Acknowledging and acting on conflicts of interest as they arise, taking appropriate action, which may include determining where a member should abstain from an activity or decision; and Performing such other duties as may be required by the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group from time to time. The duties of the Secretary comprise: In conjunction with the Convenor, giving notification of all meetings; Preparing the agenda of meetings, table correspondence and record the attendance of all persons present; Ensuring that minutes are kept of all meetings of the WG and that an update of the minutes is distributed within 28 days; Maintaining and updating a draft agenda for the next meeting and ensure that all parties are kept informed of this agenda; Co-ordinating the correspondence of the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group; and Performing such other duties as the WG may from time to time determine. The duties of the Delegate to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 People with Disabilities Working Group comprise: Report back to the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group about meetings of the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 People with Disabilities Working Group (AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group); Seek guidance from the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group about decisions being made at AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group meetings; Represent decisions relevant to the AGAttorney-General-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group made by the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group at meetings; and Compiling an Annual Report to the Annual State Conference. The duties of the Technical Assistant/Accessibility Liaison comprise: Organising the technological side of meetings; and Ensuring that meetings are accessible, including with interpreters.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will: Work with Greens local, state and federal representatives to review, develop and recommend policies across disability and other portfolios to ensure they are accessible and equitable for people with disabilities; Support and advocate for people with disabilities to take up membership, leadership roles and candidacy for the party; Be an education resource and reference for people within the party on disability policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do and practice; and Engage with federal and other state Greens disability working groups. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will, in the first instance, collaborate with and take the advice of people with specific disabilities where activities or decisions of the group relate to that specific disability. This includes consultation about which experts are invited to participate in the group.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group has no authority to incur debts or secure loans on behalf of the party. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will only expend funds provided by the party where this is an accordance with a budget that has been ratified by State Council. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group Convenor will be responsible for approving expenditure in the budget, although any member may request funding for activities. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group Convenor is responsible for acquittal in coordination with the State Treasurer. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group may be allocated a budget by State Council to cover the costs of hiring Auslan interpreters for meetings, 5.c.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will meet not less than four times per year either in person, via video link up or by any other appropriate method available. Where possible, meetings will be facilitated by a trained and experienced facilitator. The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will develop agreed procedures for the conduct of meetings, and actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 in accordance with Victorian Greens meeting procedures. All members of the group must be given a previously agreed time to review draft documents submitted in the name of the group before they are submitted and be given the opportunity to recommend changes to them.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group is an ongoing policya statement of principle and intent about what government should do and campaigning Working Group. In the event that the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group fails to meet its minimum meeting requirement for the twelve-month period between State Conferences or fails to present a report to State Conference, then a VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group dissolution item will be put on the Annual State Conference agenda.

The VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group will provide a brief written report to the State Council meeting immediately following a general election on any campaigning undertaken, with a more comprehensive report to be tabled at each Annual State conference. The report to Annual State Conference must detail as a minimum: Current membership; Report from the VGVictorian Greens-PDWGParticipatory Democracy Working Group delegate to the Australian Greensthe Australian Greens (The Greens) Incorporated, incorporated under the *Associations Incorporation Act 1991* (ACT) with association number A02626 People with Disabilities Working Group; Details of meeting activity; and Progress on areas that are within the roles of the Working Group as defined in the terms of reference.

documents.t: In this item, specified person or body means: the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1); another political partya political party registered under Commonwealth, state or territory law; a member who holds public officeincludes a member elected or appointed to a public office where the term of that office is yet to begin; and a member of another political partya political party registered under Commonwealth, state or territory law who holds public officean elected office in a council or parliament. A member is eligible for election as a State Councillor if they: have been a member for the past two years, ignoring any gap of less than 30 days; and live in Victoria. A member is not eligible for election as a State Councillor if they: have held that office for two consecutive terms (of whatever length) and either they are still in office or they have not yet spent seven months out of office; are a member of the same branch as three continuing State Councillors; in the last year, have been a member of the Constitutional Votes Committee; in the last year, have been a member who holds public office; have been an employee or a member of the staff of a specified person or body and the period that has elapsed since they were last so employed is less than the cumulative total period for which they were so employed during the last two years; are a represented person within the meaning of the Guardianship and Administration Actthe Associations Incorporation Reform Act 2012 2019; or in the last five years, have been: suspended for a period of three months or more, or expelled, from the Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) or another Greens partyone of the member bodies of the Australian Greens; insolvent under administrationhas the meaning given in the Interpretation of Legislation Act 1984, or the equivalent status under the law of another state or territory; disqualified under Australian law from managing a corporation or co‑operative; or imprisoned for an offence involving dishonesty.

A member is eligible to be appointed as a State Councillor if they: are a First Nations member; are eligible for election as a State Councillor, excluding the requirements in items 4(3) (a), (b) and (g)(ii), (iii) and (iv). A member is not eligible to be appointed as a State Councillor if they: are insolvent under administrationhas the meaning given in the Interpretation of Legislation Act 1984, or the equivalent status under the law of another state or territory; or are disqualified under Australian law from managing a corporation or co-operative.

A member is eligible to be appointed to the Constitutional Votes Committee if they: are eligible for election as a State Councillor, excluding the requirements in items 4(3)(a), (b) and (c); in the last year, have not been a State Councillor; are not a candidate, or a nominee to be a candidate, for election to State Council. are not currently seeking to be certified as eligible to be appointed as a State Councillor or to the pool under Schedule 7; and are not a member of the pool under Schedule 7. Sub-item (1) does not apply to an appointment under clause 28(4)(b).

All expenditure approvals must be allocated to an item in the current approved AGVAustralian Greens Victoria budget. Once the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria budget is approved, any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria members who are solely or jointly responsible for expenditure decisions are responsible for only approving expenditure within the approved budget, unless they gain approval from FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee for a budget adjustment to accommodate the increased spend. The State Director is responsible for authorising expenditure within the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria budget, subject to the following conditions: The State Council has approved that a committee or working group is accountable for a specific budget item, in which case responsibility passes to that committee or working group. The State Director has delegated expenditure authorisation for specific budget items to AGVAustralian Greens Victoria staff. In such an event, the State Director still retains accountability for the budget item against which the authority has been delegated. Where expenditure will result in the relevant budget item being exceeded by no more than $5,000, the State Director must nominate an alternate budget item or items to be reduced by the same value. An expenditure increase of more than $5,000 shall be referred to FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee for consideration and if appropriate, funds reallocation within the approved budget. In event that the State Director takes leave, they must delegate their authorities temporarily to another AGVAustralian Greens Victoria staff member/s or State Office Bearer. Delegation of authority shall be in writing and shall indicate the period for such delegation applies and/or when such delegation expires. In the event that State Council or State Executive has revoked a delegate's authorities and the State Director is on a leave of absence, authorities pass to the AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary. The AGVAustralian Greens Victoria Secretary can temporarily assume the authorities of the State Director in the event of: The State Director is on a leave of absence and has not delegated their authorities; or The State Director or AGVAustralian Greens Victoria staff member to whom authority has been delegated in the State Director's absence, is unable to make the authorisation before the payment by the time it falls due. In the event that a committee or working group is allocated a budget, the convener of the committee or working group is accountable for: Creating a detailed budget for how the funds allocated to the group or committee should be spent. Approving spending in accordance with that budget. Ensuring that expenditure is only made in accordance with that budget. FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee and State Executive must be notified by email or other written communication of any delegation of spending authority. Any AGVAustralian Greens Victoria member or Partythe incorporated association referred to in clause 40(1) body may put forward an expenditure or income proposal to FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee for review. The proposal should include details of the expenditure (or income) including, but not limited to, the cost and benefits of accepting the proposal. Following FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee's review of the expenditure/income proposal, FAICFinance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee can do any of the following: approve the proposal if the amount in question is less than $5000 and corresponding budget offsets can be found or in line with the powers granted in the Finance, Administration and Infrastructure Committee Bylaw. recommend the proposal to State Council for approval; or return the proposal to the proposer requesting further detail; or choose not to recommend the proposal for approval. State Council must approve expenditure outside the existing AGVAustralian Greens Victoria budget that will alter the bottom line. By approving such proposals, State Council is acknowledging that the additional expenditure will result in a reduction in the surplus or increase in the deficit.
